Data Visualization: ggplot part 2

Learning Goals

At the end of this exercise, you will be able to:
1. Build stacked bar plots of categorical variables.
2. Build side-by-side barplots using position= "dodge".
3. Build histograms and density plots.
4. Create new categories with case_when().

2. It should have a mix of categorical and continuous variables.
3. Know your audience- don’t be too hip for the room.
4. Be polite.

A few more useful aesthetics

There are many options to create nice plots in ggplot. One useful trick is to store the plot as a new object and then experiment with geom’s and aesthetics.

p <- homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x= log10.mass, y= log10.hra))
#P stored, now you can play with different geoms and aesthetics

Play with point size.

p +geom_point(size=0.75)

Map shapes to another categorical variable.

p+geom_point(aes(color=thermoregulation), size=1.75)

#Coloring by caegorical variable
p+geom_point(aes(shape=thermoregulation, color=thermoregulation), size=1.75)

#Helps differentiate further
#Consider who will be reading your report, and be aware of colorblindness!

Barplots and multiple variables

At this point you should be comfortable building bar plots that shows counts of observations using geom_bar(). Last time we explored the fill option in box plots as a way to bring color to the plot; i.e. we filled by the same variable that we were plotting. What happens when we fill by a different categorical variable?

Let’s start by counting how many observations we have in each taxonomic group.

homerange %>% count(taxon, sort=T)
## # A tibble: 9 x 2
##   taxon             n
##   <chr>         <int>
## 1 mammals         238
## 2 birds           140
## 3 marine fishes    90
## 4 snakes           41
## 5 river fishes     14
## 6 turtles          14
## 7 tortoises        12
## 8 lizards          11
## 9 lake fishes       9
#Sort our via descending order by sort=T

Now let’s make a bar plot of these data.

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxon)) + geom_bar() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Observations by Taxon in Homerange Data",
       x = "Taxonomic Group")

#X axis is categorical variable

By specifying fill=trophic.guild we build a stacked bar plot that shows the proportion of a given taxonomic group that is an herbivore or carnivore.

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxon, fill = trophic.guild)) + geom_bar() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Observations by Taxon in Homerange Data",
       x = "Taxonomic Group",
       fill = "Trophic Guild")

#Not always helpful becuase ex. how many carnivores are there?

We can also have counts of each trophic guild within taxonomic group shown side-by-side by specifying position="dodge".

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxon, fill = trophic.guild)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Observations by Taxon in Homerange Data",
       x = "Taxonomic Group",
       fill = "Trophic Guild")

#Dodge lets you build a side-by-side bar plot by variable

Here is the same plot oriented vertically.

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxon, fill = trophic.guild)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title = "Observations by Taxon in Homerange Data",
       x = "Taxonomic Group",
       fill= "Trophic Guild")

#Position dodge, but now doing vertically. end up with annoying problem with X axis, so adjusting angle of X axis degrees by 60!
#hjust = 0 will bring words into graph since you rotated. But once you settle on aesthetic you like, you can copy and paste throughout your project

We can also scale all bars to a percentage (or proportion).

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxon, fill = trophic.guild))+
  geom_bar(position = position_fill())+ 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+
  coord_flip()

#Scaling bars and only showing as a percentage

penguins %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=island))+geom_bar()

#Counts of penguins per island
penguins %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=island, fill=species))+geom_bar(position="dodge")

#Number of species per island
  1. What are the number of individuals separated by sex on each island?
penguins %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=island, fill=sex))+geom_bar(position="dodge")

#To remove NAs:
penguins %>% 
  filter(sex!="NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=island, fill=sex))+geom_bar(position="dodge")

Using group

In addition to fill, group is an aesthetic that accomplishes the same function but does not add color.

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = class, y = log10.mass)) +
  geom_boxplot()

I use group to make individual box plots for each taxon.

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = class, y = log10.mass, group = taxon)) +
  geom_boxplot()

#Use group for categorical variable But group doesn't color things

I can also use fill to associate the different taxa with a color coded key.

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = class, y = log10.mass, fill = taxon)) +
  geom_boxplot()

#Fill things in with color
#Outline in color:
homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = class, y = log10.mass, color = taxon)) +
  geom_boxplot()

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = class, y = log10.mass, fill = class)) +
  geom_boxplot()

We can make bar plots of 2 kinds. Boxplos with range of given continous varbale by categorical. Scatterplots. Colors. Point sizes. Adding lables to axis to be clear to readers. Practice all of these for HW! Add the aesthetics that you need, like labels and titles so that your report is clean and professional-looking!

When you knit graphs, images are stored with keep.md file because github will call those images when they get that folder.
